(41, 5, 34, 44, 14, 9, 9, 'thy faith hath made thee whole', 'Faith and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of faith in healing. In Mark, Jesus acknowledges the woman''s faith as the source of her wholeness, while in Acts, Paul recognizes the man''s faith as a precursor to his healing.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 34, 41, 10, 52, 52, 'thy faith hath made thee whole', 'Connection of Faith and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the role of faith in healing. In each instance, Jesus declares that faith has made the individuals whole, highlighting a consistent theme of faith leading to restoration.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 34, 40, 9, 2, 2, 'thy faith hath made thee whole', 'Connection of Healing and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the role of faith in healing. In Mark, Jesus acknowledges the woman''s faith as the source of her wholeness, while in Matthew, he sees the faith of those bringing the paralytic and responds with forgiveness and encouragement.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 42, 8, 49, 49, NULL, 'Parallel Accounts of a Miracle', 'Both passages emphasize the moment when news arrives that the ruler''s daughter has died, indicating a critical turning point in the narrative. The phrasing in both accounts is nearly identical, highlighting the urgency and despair of the situation.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 43, 11, 39, 39, 'Thy daughter is dead', 'Death and Resurrection Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of death and the response to it. In both passages, the characters confront the reality of death, with the ruler''s daughter being declared dead and Lazarus having been dead for four days.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 41, 5, 22, 22, 'ruler of the synagogue', 'Connection of Jairus'' Faith', 'Both passages emphasize Jairus'' desperation and faith in Jesus. In Mark 5:22, Jairus approaches Jesus in humility, while in Mark 5:35, the news of his daughter''s death challenges that faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 41, 10, 17, 17, 'troublest thou the Master any further', 'Seeking Help from Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of approaching Jesus for assistance. In Mark 5:35, the ruler seeks Jesus to heal his daughter, while in Mark 10:17, a man kneels to ask how to inherit eternal life, indicating a desire for spiritual guidance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 42, 7, 6, 7, NULL, 'Authority and Worthiness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worthiness in approaching Jesus. In Mark, the ruler is told not to trouble Jesus further, while in Luke, the centurion expresses his unworthiness for Jesus to enter his house.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 43, 5, 25, 25, 'Thy daughter is dead', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection and life. In Mark 5:35, the announcement of death contrasts with John 5:25, which speaks of the dead hearing and living again.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 35, 40, 26, 18, 18, 'the Master', 'Connection of Authority and Timing', 'This connection highlights the use of the term ''Master'' in both passages, emphasizing the authority of Jesus in different contexts. In Mark, the ruler refers to Jesus as ''Master'' in a moment of desperation, while in Matthew, Jesus identifies himself as ''the Master'' in relation to the Passover, indicating his control over the situation.', 'keyword', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 42, 8, 50, 50, 'Be not afraid, only believe', 'Connection of Fear and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''fear not'' and the call to ''believe'' in the face of distress. This connection highlights the importance of faith in overcoming fear during critical moments.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 40, 9, 28, 29, 'only believe', 'Connection of Faith and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith in both passages. In Mark, Jesus encourages belief without fear, while in Matthew, he emphasizes the importance of faith for healing.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 43, 11, 40, 40, 'only believe', 'Connection of Belief and Seeing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in experiencing divine intervention. In Mark, Jesus encourages belief to overcome fear, while in John, belief is linked to witnessing God''s glory.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 41, 9, 23, 23, 'only believe', 'Connection of Belief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief as essential for experiencing the power of Jesus. Both passages emphasize the necessity of faith, with Jesus encouraging belief in challenging circumstances.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 45, 4, 18, 24, 'only believe', 'Faith in God''s Promises', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in God''s promises despite seemingly impossible circumstances. Both passages emphasize the importance of faith, as seen in Jesus'' encouragement to ''only believe'' and Abraham''s unwavering faith in God''s promise.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 41, 5, 34, 34, 'only believe', 'Connection of Faith and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith in the process of healing. In Mark 5:34, the woman''s faith leads to her wholeness, while in Mark 5:36, Jesus encourages belief to overcome fear.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 36, 43, 4, 48, 50, 'only believe', 'Faith in Jesus'' Words', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in Jesus'' words. In Mark, Jesus encourages the ruler not to fear but to believe, while in John, the nobleman believes Jesus'' promise about his son’s healing.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 37, 41, 14, 33, 33, NULL, 'Discipleship and Intimacy', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Peter, James, and John, highlighting their unique role among the disciples. This connection illustrates their closeness to Jesus during significant moments.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 37, 44, 9, 40, 40, 'Peter', 'Peter''s Role in Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s significant role in miraculous events. In Mark, he is one of the chosen disciples, while in Acts, he performs a miracle by raising Tabitha.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 37, 41, 9, 2, 2, 'Peter, and James, and John', 'Discipleship of Peter, James, John', 'Both passages emphasize the selectivity of Jesus in choosing Peter, James, and John to accompany him during significant events. This connection highlights their special role among the disciples in witnessing key moments of Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 37, 47, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Witnesses and Testimony Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of having multiple witnesses to establish truth. In Mark, Peter, James, and John are chosen witnesses, while 2 Corinthians emphasizes that every word is established by two or three witnesses.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 37, 42, 8, 51, 51, 'save Peter, and James, and John', 'Disciples Present in Both Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Peter, James, and John during a significant event. This connection highlights their role as key witnesses in the narrative.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 40, 9, 23, 24, 'tumult, and them that wept and wailed greatly', 'Connection of Mourning and Response', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of mourners at the ruler''s house. In Mark, there is ''tumult'' and ''wept and wailed greatly,'' while in Matthew, there are ''minstrels and the people making a noise.'' This connection highlights the contrasting reactions to Jesus'' declaration about the girl''s condition.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 42, 8, 52, 53, NULL, 'Connection of Mourning and Skepticism', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of mourning, as seen in the weeping and wailing. Additionally, the reaction to Jesus'' statement about death highlights a shared theme of disbelief in the face of his words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 24, 9, 17, 20, 'wept and wailed greatly', 'Connection of Mourning and Wailing', 'This connection highlights the theme of mourning and wailing present in both passages. In Mark 5:38, the tumult and weeping reflect the sorrowful atmosphere, while Jeremiah 9:17-20 explicitly calls for mourning women to lament, emphasizing the cultural practice of expressing grief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 40, 11, 17, 17, 'wept and wailed greatly', 'Connection of Mourning and Lamenting', 'This connection highlights the themes of mourning and lamentation present in both passages. Mark 5:38 describes a scene of weeping, while Matthew 11:17 mentions mourning and lamenting, emphasizing the emotional responses to grief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 41, 5, 22, 22, 'ruler of the synagogue', 'Connection of Jairus and Tumult', 'Both passages emphasize the ruler of the synagogue, Jairus, and the tumult surrounding his daughter''s condition. The weeping and wailing in the house reflect the urgency and desperation that led Jairus to seek Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 38, 44, 9, 39, 39, 'wept and wailed greatly', 'Expressions of Grief', 'Both passages emphasize the act of weeping in response to death. In Mark, the tumult and weeping signify mourning, while in Acts, the widows weep and show garments made by Dorcas, highlighting their loss.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 39, 44, 20, 10, 10, 'the damsel is not dead, but sleepeth', 'Connection of Life and Sleep', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of life being present despite appearances of death. In Mark, Jesus states the girl is merely sleeping, while in Acts, Paul reassures others that the young man’s life is still in him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 39, 52, 5, 10, 10, 'sleepeth', 'Connection of Sleep and Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of sleep as a metaphor for death in both passages. Mark 5:39 refers to the damsel as ''sleepeth,'' while 1 Thessalonians 5:10 contrasts ''wake or sleep'' in the context of life with Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
